ution to gender and genre theory as well as cultural criticism of the contemporary. It will appeal to scholars in a wide range of fields and become essential for students of the Gothic, contemporary fiction – particularly Alice Munro and Margaret Atwood – and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGothic literaturexWomen authors. 0aGothic revival (Literature)xWomen authors. 0aGothic revival (Literature)zCanada. 0aHorror films. 0aHorror tales, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures and women. 4aGothic 2017. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aAlice Munro.  aAritha van Herk.  aCanadian fiction.  aGothic dress texture.  aGothic forms.  aHaunted Houses.  aLady Oracle.  aLives of Girls and Women.  aMargaret Atwood.  aNo Fixed Address.  afeminine texts.  aglobal escapes.  aneo-Gothicism.1 aBecker, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612537840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125378/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles